This video describes a destructive pattern I’ve observed in certain social media lives — and, in hindsight, across various moments in my life.

It often begins with resonance: a shared experience, familiar language, or insight that feels true. But once engagement begins, that resonance can be inverted into control. Belonging becomes conditional. Questioning is punished. Compliance replaces understanding.

Over time, the structure is reinforced not only by those who lead it, but by participants who echo the narrative, reward conformity, and amplify disconnection. Authority benefits those at the center, while others are governed without truly belonging.

This dynamic has been recognized for a long time. As Scripture warns:

“The kings of the Gentiles lord it over them; and those who exercise authority over them call themselves benefactors.”
— Luke 22:25–26

In its most extreme form, this pattern escalates into framing self-destruction as escape.

This is not philosophy.
This is not spirituality.
It is a destructive psychological pattern.

Truth does not require self-destruction.
Life remains the reference point.

