<div class=chatlog__message-group><div id=chatlog__message-container-1483198430175297689 class=chatlog__message-container data-message-id=1483198430175297689><div class=chatlog__message><div class=chatlog__message-aside><img class=chatlog__avatar src=https://cdn.discordapp.com/embed/avatars/4.png alt=Avatar loading=lazy></div><div class=chatlog__message-primary><div class=chatlog__header><span class=chatlog__author title=dadventuressteve data-user-id=1264035953933156432>Veilocity</span> <span class=chatlog__timestamp title="Tuesday, 17 March 2026 12:21 AM"><a href=#chatlog__message-container-1483198430175297689>17/03/2026 12:21 AM</a></span></div><div class="chatlog__content chatlog__markdown"><span class=chatlog__markdown-preserve><strong>&quot;Peace be with you… and also with you.&quot; ✨ 30/09/2025 - Albania</strong>

But when I say that, how does it land? Do you just hear the words, or do you feel them? What could you shift in your life—inside and out—so that peace isn’t just spoken, but embodied?
Too often, we reach for fleeting experiences to distract ourselves, because real confrontation feels uncomfortable. But that’s the miracle of Jesus: He shows us how to reconcile peace, justice, and righteousness by letting go into God.
Still—there’s a fine line. The church has sometimes taught self-abandonment, and that is not the way. The call is to surrender what we cannot carry alone, but not to erase who we are.
Holding that balance—that’s the key to ushering in the Kingdom of Heaven on Earth. <img
    loading="lazy"
    class="chatlog__emoji "
    alt="🌍"
    title="earth_africa"
    src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/twitter/twemoji@latest/assets/svg/1f30d.svg">✨

