<div class=chatlog__message-group><div id=chatlog__message-container-1496527157952774184 class=chatlog__message-container data-message-id=1496527157952774184><div class=chatlog__message><div class=chatlog__message-aside><img class=chatlog__avatar src=https://cdn.discordapp.com/embed/avatars/4.png alt=Avatar loading=lazy></div><div class=chatlog__message-primary><div class=chatlog__header><span class=chatlog__author title=dadventuressteve data-user-id=1264035953933156432>Veilocity</span> <span class=chatlog__timestamp title="Wednesday, 22 April 2026 7:04 PM"><a href=#chatlog__message-container-1496527157952774184>22/04/2026 7:04 PM</a></span></div><div class="chatlog__content chatlog__markdown"><span class=chatlog__markdown-preserve><strong>Being a Good Shepherd…” ≠ trafficking people <img
    loading="lazy"
    class="chatlog__emoji "
    alt="♻"
    title="♻"
    src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/twitter/twemoji@latest/assets/svg/267b.svg">️ 18/11/2025 – VOID</strong>

A shepherd protects autonomy — never replaces it. A trafficker profits from its loss.
And sometimes what looks like care… is just processing.

“Thou shalt not kill.” — Exodus 20:13

Not just the body — but the spirit, the will, the autonomy within.
Where there is coercion, dependency, or control, something has already gone wrong.

Care doesn’t consume. Guidance doesn’t erase.
And I’m not here to be broken down into something more convenient.

Discernment is remembering the difference.

